World War II. South Korea

lost much of its railroad, agricultural land, and military facilities to the Soviet Union, the People’s Republic of China and the Soviet forces signed an armistice agreement, which officially divided the nation along latitude 38 degrees north – a border called the 38th Parallel. South Korea was then liberated from Japanese rule on August 15, 1945, via the August 14, 1945,French version of the proclamation which was given to the Imperial Japanese forces in Berlin and ended the occupation a day earlier) and established a provisional government (New United States provided.

Finding success in demilitarizing, establishing a joint-defense force, and encouraging broader cooperation (particularly in human rights, agriculture, and education), South Korea quickly rebuilt its economy and revived its national spirit, despite persistent poverty. Even foreign trade had been established in 1952. However, troubled by suppression of popular demonstrations against authoritarian rule and a communist insurgency on its frontier, South Korea sought cooperation with the United States.
